    slug: "hajj-aur-umrah-kay-masail",
    description: `Hajj aur Umrah Kay Masail is an Urdu-language Islamic jurisprudence book that provides a comprehensive and systematic guide to the rulings, regulations, and practical procedures governing the performance of Hajj and Umrah according to Islamic law. The title translates to "Issues and Rulings of Hajj and Umrah," and the book is structured as a practical reference manual that addresses virtually every question and scenario a pilgrim might encounter before, during, and after the pilgrimage. Written by a qualified scholar with deep expertise in the fiqh of Hajj and Umrah, the book draws upon the Quran, authentic hadith, and the established rulings of the major schools of Islamic jurisprudence to provide reliable and well-sourced answers to common and uncommon questions alike.

The book begins with the foundational rulings on Hajj and Umrah, including the obligation of Hajj, its conditions (such as financial ability, physical capability, and the presence of a mahram for women), the different types of Hajj (Hajj al-Ifrad, Hajj al-Qiran, and Hajj at-Tamattu'), and their respective rulings. It then provides a detailed, step-by-step guide to each stage of the pilgrimage, starting with entering the state of ihram at the designated miqat points, performing the tawaf (circumambulation) of the Kaabah, the sa'i (walking between Safa and Marwah), standing at Arafat, the stoning of the Jamaraat, the sacrifice, shaving or trimming the hair, and the farewell tawaf. For each ritual, the book explains the obligatory (fard) and necessary (wajib) elements, the recommended (sunnah) acts, the things that are prohibited, and the expiation required for mistakes or omissions.

The book also covers a wide range of practical scenarios and special circumstances that pilgrims frequently encounter. These include rulings for women pilgrims (menstruation during ihram, pregnancy, traveling without a mahram), rulings for elderly and disabled pilgrims (performing tawaf in a wheelchair, having someone else stone the Jamaraat on one's behalf), rulings for medical emergencies (taking medication, receiving injections, undergoing surgery while in ihram), and rulings for common mistakes (forgetting to perform a wajib act, performing rituals in the wrong order, violating the ihram restrictions unintentionally). The Urdu prose is clear and accessible, with Arabic terms explained in simple language and Quranic verses and hadith provided with Urdu translations. This book is widely used by Urdu-speaking pilgrims as a travel companion and reference guide, and by imams and teachers who conduct Hajj and Umrah training courses in mosques and Islamic centers throughout Pakistan, India, and other Urdu-speaking communities around the world.`,
